<methodology slug="requirements-lifecycle">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>ba</group>
    <domain>business-analyst</domain>
    <summary>Governance framework managing requirements through eight states with formal change control, version history, and audit trails to prevent scope changes.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>requirements</tag>
      <tag>lifecycle</tag>
      <tag>change-control</tag>
      <tag>governance</tag>
      <tag>compliance</tag>
    </tags>
    <category>requirements</category>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-28</created>
    <related>
      <ref slug="requirements-traceability"/>
      <ref slug="requirements-validation"/>
    </related>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Requirements Lifecycle Management</title>
    <summary>A governance framework for managing requirements from initial capture through implementation and verification. Defines eight requirement states (Draft → Proposed → Approved → Implemented → Verified, plus Rejected/Deferred/Deleted), enforces change control via a formal change request process, and maintains version history for every requirement. Prevents uncontrolled scope changes and preserves the audit trail needed for compliance and retrospectives.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Requirements exist in multiple versions with no clarity on which is current; approved requirements change without process; implementation diverges from documentation; nobody can reconstruct the evolution at project end. A lifecycle model with explicit states and a change request gate eliminates version confusion and creates an audit trail that satisfies both governance and postmortem needs.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Projects with formal change control requirements (regulated industries, government, enterprise IT)</item>
        <item>Long-running projects where requirements evolve over months and version drift is a real risk</item>
        <item>Teams where stakeholders or developers frequently bypass the BA to change requirements informally</item>
        <item>Compliance context (SOX, ISO, HIPAA) requiring a documented requirements audit trail</item>
        <item>Post-implementation review revealed implementation mismatches — lifecycle management prevents recurrence</item>
        <item>Integrating multiple delivery streams that each own a subset of requirements</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Early-stage discovery / hypothesis testing where requirements legitimately change every sprint — add lifecycle overhead only after problem-solution fit</item>
        <item>Tiny internal tools with a single stakeholder and a one-week delivery — a shared doc suffices</item>
        <item>Pure agile backlogs managed in Jira/Linear where the tool already enforces state — duplicate governance adds friction without value</item>
        <item>Throwaway prototypes — formal lifecycle governance is wasted on artifacts designed to be discarded</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="six-lifecycle-stages">
      <rule>
        <statement>Every requirement must pass through six stages in sequence: Identify (discover from sources), Analyze (categorize, detect conflicts, prioritize), Specify (formal documentation with ID and template), Validate (confirm correctness with stakeholders), Verify (confirm implementation matches spec), Manage (version control, change control, traceability).</statement>
        <rationale>Skipping stages produces requirements that are captured but not analyzed, or documented but never validated — the most common sources of implementation mismatch.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="eight-requirement-states">
      <rule>
        <statement>Every requirement must be in exactly one of: Draft, Proposed, Approved, Rejected, Implemented, Verified, Deferred, Deleted. State must be visible in the requirements register at all times.</statement>
        <rationale>Hidden state produces version confusion; teams implement Rejected requirements or skip Deferred ones because state is not tracked explicitly.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Valid transitions: Draft → Proposed → Approved → Implemented → Verified. From Proposed: also Rejected or Deferred. From Approved: also Deferred. Deferred requirements return to Proposed in a later cycle. No other transitions are permitted without a change request.</statement>
        <rationale>Restricting transitions prevents backward-state corruption (e.g. moving Implemented back to Draft) which breaks traceability and audit trails.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="validation-vs-verification">
      <rule>
        <statement>Validation answers "Are we building the right thing?" — conducted during requirements using stakeholder reviews, walkthroughs, and prototype reviews. Verification answers "Are we building it right?" — conducted after implementation using testing, code inspection, and user acceptance.</statement>
        <rationale>Conflating validation and verification causes teams to skip one or the other; "requirements review" is not a substitute for post-implementation testing.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="requirements-attributes">
      <p>Track these attributes for every requirement: ID (unique, immutable), Name (short title), Description (full text), Status (current state), Priority (MoSCoW or 1-5), Source (stakeholder or document), Owner (responsible role), Version (current version number), Created (date), Modified (last update date), Author (who wrote it).</p>
    </section>

    <section name="change-request-process">
      <rule>
        <statement>Every change to an Approved or Implemented requirement must be initiated via a formal change request that documents the current text, proposed change, reason, and impact analysis across requirements, design, development, testing, schedule, and cost before any approval decision.</statement>
        <rationale>Ad-hoc changes without impact analysis produce cascading failures: a changed requirement breaks test cases, design documents, and dependent requirements without anyone knowing.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Change requests must be approved by at minimum the BA (requirements impact), project manager (schedule and cost impact), and sponsor (business decision). All approvals must be recorded with name, decision, and date.</statement>
        <rationale>Single-approver change control is bypassed under schedule pressure; multi-role sign-off distributes accountability and forces the full impact to be acknowledged.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>When a change request is approved, increment the requirement version number and create a new version history entry with the change description, author, and date before updating the requirement text.</statement>
        <rationale>In-place edits without version history make it impossible to reconstruct what was approved at each point in time — a critical audit trail requirement.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="common-mistakes">
      <antipattern>
        <description>No version control — teams work from the "latest" document without knowing if they have the current version.</description>
        <reason>Use numbered versions and a single authoritative location; version history must be auditable to support compliance reviews.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Skipping validation — assuming requirements are correct because stakeholders provided them.</description>
        <reason>Stakeholders state what they think they want, not necessarily what they need; walkthroughs and prototype reviews surface misunderstandings before development starts.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Status not updated — requirements tracking becomes fiction because nobody updates state after approvals and implementations.</description>
        <reason>Define who is responsible for status updates at each stage transition and make it a team ritual, not an optional task.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>No baseline — cannot compare current requirements to approved version to measure scope creep.</description>
        <reason>Baseline at each major milestone (project kickoff, sprint planning, release) and store the baseline snapshot separately from the working document.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="examples">
      <example type="good" title="State History Example: REQ-045 Password Reset">
        <code lang="markdown"><![CDATA[
| Date   | State Change                  | Trigger                          |
|--------|-------------------------------|----------------------------------|
| Jan 5  | (none) → Draft                | Created from stakeholder interview |
| Jan 8  | Draft → Proposed              | BA review complete, ready for sign-off |
| Jan 10 | Proposed → Approved           | Stakeholder sign-off obtained    |
| Jan 25 | Approved → Implemented        | Development complete, PR merged  |
| Feb 1  | Implemented → Verified        | Acceptance testing passed, UAT sign-off |
        ]]></code>
        <note>Each state change recorded with date and trigger — provides full audit trail without searching email threads.</note>
      </example>
      <example type="good" title="Change Request Example: CR-012">
        <code lang="markdown"><![CDATA[
Change Request: CR-012 — Modify Login Session Timeout
Requestor: Product Owner
Affected: REQ-030 (Session Management)

Current requirement: Session expires after 15 minutes of inactivity.
Proposed change: Session expires after 60 minutes of inactivity.
Reason: Users report being logged out mid-workflow; support tickets
  indicate 30% of password reset requests follow a session timeout.

Impact analysis:
- Requirements: REQ-030 v1.0 → v2.0 required; REQ-031 (Security Policy)
    must be reviewed for compliance with session security standards.
- Design: Session token TTL configuration in AuthService.
- Development: Config change only, no new code.
- Testing: TC-050, TC-051 require timeout value update.
- Schedule: 2-day effort, no sprint impact.
- Cost: No additional cost.

Decision: Approved with modification — 30 minutes (not requested 60 minutes).
  Security review rejected 60 minutes as non-compliant with policy.

Result: REQ-030 updated to v2.0 with 30-minute timeout. Version history entry added.
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>Treat the requirements repository as a flat directory of Markdown files (requirements/REQ-XXX.md) with YAML frontmatter holding state, version, owner, and timestamps. Subagents read the frontmatter, propose a transition, and emit a structured patch (diff or JSON) — never write the file directly without a human or gate agent reviewing. The lifecycle becomes a state machine implemented as a Makefile / script: make req-propose ID=045, make req-approve ID=045, each invoking a Claude subagent with the relevant prompt template.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="recommended-subagents">
      <list>
        <item>faion-sdd-executor-agent — drives the lifecycle as SDD tasks; each transition (Propose → Approve, Approve → Implemented) is a TASK with its own commit and execution report. Maps cleanly to the existing .aidocs/ flow.</item>
        <item>password-scrubber-agent — runs over requirement docs before they are committed to public repos, catching leaked secrets in pasted stakeholder transcripts.</item>
        <item>Custom ba-lifecycle-agent (model: sonnet) — owns Identify → Specify, including categorization, conflict detection, ID assignment.</item>
        <item>Custom ba-validator-agent (model: opus) — owns the Validate gate — runs INVEST / SMART / testability checks and either approves or returns a list of defects to fix.</item>
        <item>Custom ba-change-impact-agent (model: opus) — produces the impact-analysis section of every CR by walking the traceability graph.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="prompt-pattern">
      <p>Two-shot pattern: state read → transition proposal.</p>
      <code lang="text"><![CDATA[You are the BA lifecycle agent. The requirement below is in state {current_state}.
Allowed next states: {next_states}. Apply the transition rules from
requirements-lifecycle/README.md.

Return strict JSON:
{ "req_id": "REQ-045", "from": "Proposed", "to": "Approved" | "Rejected" | "Deferred",
  "version_bump": "patch|minor|major|none", "rationale": "<=2 sentences",
  "blocking_issues": [] }

REQUIREMENT:
---
{frontmatter + body}
---]]></code>
      <p>For change requests, prefix with: Walk the traceability matrix in requirements-traceability/ and list every artifact (REQ, design doc, test case) the proposed change touches. Produce CR-XXX in the template from requirements-lifecycle/templates.md.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="cli-tools">
      <list>
        <item>git + git log --follow — Native version history per requirement file (replaces hand-rolled version table). preinstalled</item>
        <item>pre-commit + custom hook — Block commits where a requirement transitions to a state that violates the rules in README. https://pre-commit.com</item>
        <item>yq — Read/update YAML frontmatter (yq -i '.status = "Approved"') in pipelines. brew install yq / apt install yq</item>
        <item>gh issue / gh pr — Mirror REQ states into GitHub issues so non-BA stakeholders see them in their tool. https://cli.github.com</item>
        <item>reqif-tools (open-source) — Import/export ReqIF for round-tripping with Polarion / DOORS / Jama. https://github.com/strictdoc-project/reqif</item>
        <item>strictdoc — OSS requirements management tool with a CLI; can render HTML and check traceability. https://strictdoc.readthedocs.io</item>
        <item>fossil — Single-file SCM with built-in tickets — viable for very small teams as a self-contained REQ store. https://fossil-scm.org</item>
        <item>jq — Aggregate REQ frontmatter into the Status Summary table from the README template. apt install jq</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="services-and-apps">
      <list>
        <item>Jama Connect (SaaS) — Heavy enterprise; agents can read items, change state, attach approvals. OAuth.</item>
        <item>IBM DOORS Next (SaaS/on-prem) — Standards-grade traceability; OSLC is verbose, plan for adapters.</item>
        <item>Polarion ALM (SaaS/on-prem) — Strong workflow engine; map states to Polarion status field.</item>
        <item>Modern Requirements (for Azure DevOps) (SaaS) — Lifecycle on top of work items; agents drive via az boards work-item update.</item>
        <item>Helix RM (Perforce) (SaaS/on-prem) — Legacy but solid traceability; weaker LLM ecosystem.</item>
        <item>StrictDoc (OSS) — Best fit for agent workflows: text-first, git-native, deterministic.</item>
        <item>Doorstop (OSS) — Markdown + YAML, git-native, scriptable from agents.</item>
        <item>Linear (SaaS) — Treat each REQ as an issue with a custom lifecycle_state; agents transition via issueUpdate.</item>
        <item>Jira (Cloud) (SaaS) — Workflow editor maps 1:1 to lifecycle states. Watch rate limits in batch updates.</item>
        <item>Notion (SaaS) — OK for small teams; weak typing on state fields, easy to corrupt with agents.</item>
        <item>Confluence + Requirements blueprint (SaaS) — Free-text drift is high; pair with a state plugin.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="best-practices">
      <list>
        <item>Store requirements as Markdown + YAML frontmatter in git, not in a database — diffs become the version history, git blame shows the author, branches model proposed states for free.</item>
        <item>One state field, no parallel statuses. If you need workflow phase + lifecycle state, encode the secondary one as a label, not as a duplicate state machine.</item>
        <item>Make the Approved gate a pull-request approval from a named stakeholder (CODEOWNERS for requirements/). Replays the Approval table from the CR template via GitHub's UI.</item>
        <item>Bump versions only on material change: scope shift, new acceptance criterion, NFR change. Wording fixes stay in the same version.</item>
        <item>Tie every commit to a REQ ID using a Conventional Commits scope: feat(REQ-045): password reset flow. The traceability link is then queryable with git log --grep.</item>
        <item>Keep Deferred time-bounded — every Deferred requirement carries a deferred_until date; an agent runs weekly and re-proposes anything past due.</item>
        <item>Baseline = a git tag (req-baseline-2026-Q2). Compare current vs. baseline with git diff --stat baseline..HEAD -- requirements/.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="ai-agent-gotchas">
      <list>
        <item>Agents will silently invent transitions. Always pass the current state in the prompt and validate the proposed transition against NEXT (above) before persisting.</item>
        <item>LLMs conflate Validation and Verification — explicitly remind them in the system prompt with the table from the README; otherwise they will mark something Verified before any test ran.</item>
        <item>Bulk re-statusing is dangerous. Cap any agent action to N requirements per run (e.g. 10) and require human review on the diff. A runaway agent that flips 200 REQs to Approved is hard to undo.</item>
        <item>Frontmatter parsing fails silently if a stakeholder pastes Smart Quotes into YAML. Add a pre-commit hook to reject non-ASCII in keys.</item>
        <item>Change Request impact analysis must be deterministic — drive it from requirements-traceability data, not from LLM recall. Use the LLM only to phrase the impact, not to discover it.</item>
        <item>Human-in-the-loop checkpoints (mandatory): Proposed → Approved (sign-off), Approved → Implemented (PR review), Implemented → Verified (QA). The agent prepares the artifact; a human flips the state.</item>
        <item>When the agent revises a requirement, force it to emit the diff, not the full new text — easier to review and avoids whole-document rewrites that lose history.</item>
        <item>Token budget: at >500 REQs do not load the whole repo into context. Index frontmatter only (yq aggregate) and load full bodies on demand.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/requirements-status-log.md" purpose="Status summary table and per-requirement detail with current state tracking"/>
      <template path="templates/change-request.md" purpose="Change request form: current/proposed text, reason, impact analysis by area, approval table"/>
      <template path="templates/version-history.md" purpose="Per-requirement version log with change descriptions and current vs. previous content"/>
    </templates>

